      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Kashius wrote:</div><div class="orig">I'm willing to wager that that the threat system in FFXIV is similar to the system in XI where you build hate. In that case, I would think constantly using Phalanx/Heavy Slash or Stab would do well for that. Then IF the mob runs off on you, you use Voke/Taunt. This will force the mob back to you so you can block and do more Phalanx and rebuild the hate.</div></div> <br /> <br />You are correct, sir.  Voke/Taunt have a debuff that is applied to the mob when they first land that essentially causes the mob to ignore enmity tables and focus attacks on the caster of said Provoke/Taunt.  It says as much in the description of the abilities.  Tanks using those and thinking that the mob is sticking to them because of an enmity spike might want to just stop for a second and read the descriptions of the abilities they're using. <br /> <br />Assuming FFXIV borrows basic enmity rules from XI in the sense that enmity decays over time and that taking damage also further reduces your enmity, it makes sense that people who have been building enmity on a mob during the voke/taunt debuff but not taking hits will have more enmity when those debuffs wear off than the tank who has just been using Light Slash/Stab between voke/taunt.  The tank has been losing more enmity and not generating a whole lot of their own.  <br /> <br />At the end of the day, I think it's going to take having mobs introduced to the game that are tuned specifically to be fought by parties before the stubborn insistence that voke/taunt is the way to go gets beaten out of certain tanks.  I've always been an advocate of learning how to do things right from the beginning, not find a cheeseball method that works today and then having to revamp your entire approach later on when the cheesy method no longer works.</div>
